Revised text:
```
Following our exploration of charge carriers and the principles of doping, we are prepared to investigate the movement of charges within semiconductors, that is, the processes that enable the conduction of electrical current.

The Concept of Drift: It is well-established from the basics of physics and Ohm's law that materials can carry electricity when subjected to a voltage gradient, which corresponds to an electric field. This field drives the charge carriers through the material, pushing them to move from one side to another. The migration of charge carriers caused by the electric field is referred to as "drift."

Image Name: Figure 2.8 Drift in a semiconductor
Description: The image designated "Figure 2.8 Drift in a semiconductor" offers a visualization of the drift phenomenon within semiconductor materials. The diagram comprises a rectangular shape representing the semiconductor, intersected by an electric field (E), signified by a horizontal arrow stretching from left to right.

Inside the semiconductor, a series of wavy arrows depict the path that charge carriers take as they pass through the material. These arrows suggest that the charge carriers are propelled by the electric field but also collide with the atoms in the crystal lattice, leading to a wavy or erratic movement pattern. This interaction results in a cumulative drift of carriers in the direction of the electric field.

The semiconductor section is connected to a battery situated beneath it, with the positive terminal positioned on the left and the negative terminal on the right. This configuration initiates the voltage difference necessary to create the electric field across the semiconductor.

In essence, the diagram vividly illustrates the drift process, showing how charge carriers are influenced by the electric field and how their motion is marked by both acceleration and scattering due to collisions within the crystal framework.

Figure 2.8 Drift in a semiconductor.

Semiconductors exhibit analogous behavior. As depicted in Fig. 2.8, the charge carriers are propelled by the field and collide randomly with the atoms in the crystal lattice, ultimately reaching the opposite end and re-entering the battery. The forces of acceleration from the field and the impacts with the crystal structure counterbalance each other, ensuring a steady speed for the carriers. We anticipate that the speed, denoted as 'v,' is directly proportional to the strength of the electric field, 'E':

$$
\begin{equation*}
v \propto E \tag{2.13}
\end{equation*}
$$

and consequently

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=\mu E \tag{2.14}
\end{equation*}
$$

where 'μ' stands for the "mobility" and is usually stated in units of \(\mathrm{cm}^{2}/(\mathrm{V} \cdot \mathrm{s})\). For example, in silicon, the mobility of electrons, \( \mu_{n}=1350 \mathrm{~cm}^{2}/(\mathrm{V} \cdot \mathrm{s}) \), and that of holes, \( \mu_{p}=480 \mathrm{~cm}^{2}/(\mathrm{V} \cdot \mathrm{s}) \). Since electrons move in the opposite direction to the electric field, the velocity vector must be expressed as

$$
\begin{equation*}
\overrightarrow{v_{e}}=-\mu_{n} \vec{E} \tag{2.15}
\end{equation*}
```

After analyzing the pn junction in equilibrium, we can now explore its behavior under more engaging and practical conditions. Let's start by applying an external voltage across the device, as depicted in Fig. 2.23, where the voltage source makes the $n$ side more positive than the $p$ side. We refer to the junction being under "reverse bias" to highlight the connection of the positive voltage to the $n$ terminal. Whether used as a noun or a verb, "bias" signifies operation under certain "desirable" conditions. We will delve extensively into the concept of biasing in this and subsequent chapters.

