Figure 2.24 Reduction of junction capacitance with reverse bias.

We aim to reevaluate the results obtained in equilibrium for the reverse bias scenario. First, let's determine if the external voltage enhances or opposes the built-in electric field. Since, in equilibrium, $\vec{E}$ is directed from the $n$ side to the $p$ side, $V_{R}$ strengthens the field. However, a higher electric field can only be sustained if more fixed charge is available, necessitating the exposure of more acceptor and donor ions, thereby widening the depletion region.

What effect does this have on the diffusion and drift currents? Given that the external voltage intensifies the field, the barrier increases even beyond the equilibrium level, effectively preventing current flow. In other words, the junction conducts a negligible current under reverse bias. ${ }^{9}$

With no current flow, a reverse-biased pn junction might seem impractical. However, a crucial observation reveals its utility. Notably, in Fig. 2.23, as $V_{B}$ rises, more positive charge accumulates on the $n$ side and more negative charge on the $p$ side. Thus, the device functions as a capacitor [Fig. 2.24(a)]. Essentially, the conductive $n$ and $p$ sections can be viewed as the capacitor's two plates. We also assume the charge in the depletion region is equivalently distributed on each plate.

Readers might still find the device unremarkable. After all, any two parallel plates can form a capacitor, so using a pn junction for this purpose may seem unjustified. However, reverse-biased $p n$ junctions possess a unique property that proves valuable in circuit design. Referring back to Fig. 2.23, we observe that as $V_{R}$ increases, so does the width of the depletion region. Consequently, the conceptual diagram in Fig. 2.24(a) can be modified as in Fig. 2.24(b) for rising $V_{R}$ values, revealing that the capacitance decreases as the plates move apart. Thus, the junction exhibits a voltage-dependent capacitance.

It can be demonstrated that the capacitance per unit area of the junction is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j}=\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1-\frac{V_{R}}{V_{0}}}} \tag{2.75}
\end{equation*}
$$

${ }^{9}$ As detailed in Section 2.2.3, the current is not entirely zero.
where $C_{j 0}$ represents the capacitance at zero bias $\left(V_{R}=0\right)$ and $V_{0}$ is the built-in potential [Eq. (2.69)]. (This equation assumes $V_{R}$ is negative for reverse bias.) The value of $C_{j 0}$ is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j 0}=\sqrt{\frac{\epsilon_{s i} q}{2} \frac{N_{A} N_{D}}{N_{A}+N_{D}} \frac{1}{V_{0}}} \tag{2.76}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $\epsilon_{s i}$ denotes the dielectric constant of silicon, equal to $11.7 \times 8.85 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{cm} .{ }^{10}$ As plotted in Fig. 2.25, $C_{j}$ decreases with increasing $V_{R}$.
