Figure 2.25 Junction capacitance under reverse bias.

Example: A pn junction is doped with $N_{A}=2 \times 10^{16} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}$ and $N_{D}=9 \times 10^{15} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}$. Determine the capacitance for (a) $V_{R}=0$ and (b) $V_{R}=1 \mathrm{~V}$.

Solution: First, we calculate the built-in potential:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{0} & =V_{T} \ln \frac{N_{A} N_{D}}{n_{i}^{2}}  \tag{2.77}\\
& =0.73 \mathrm{~V} . \tag{2.78}
\end{align*}
$$

For $V_{R}=0$ and $q=1.6 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C}$, we have

$$
\begin{align*}
C_{j 0} & =\sqrt{\frac{\epsilon_{s i} q}{2} \frac{N_{A} N_{D}}{N_{A}+N_{D}} \cdot \frac{1}{V_{0}}}  \tag{2.79}\\
& =2.65 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{cm}^{2} . \tag{2.80}
\end{align*}
$$

In microelectronics, dealing with very small devices, we can rewrite this as

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j 0}=0.265 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2} \tag{2.81}
\end{equation*}
$$

[^9]where $1 \mathrm{fF}($ femtofarad $)=10^{-15} \mathrm{~F}$. For $V_{R}=1 \mathrm{~V}$,
\$\$

$$
\begin{align*}
C_{j} & =\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1+\frac{V_{R}}{V_{0}}}}  \tag{2.82}\\
& =0.172 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2} \tag{2.83}
\end{align*}
$$

\$\$

Exercise: Repeat the above example if the donor concentration on the $N$ side is doubled. Compare the results.

The capacitance variation with applied voltage renders the device a "nonlinear" capacitor, as it does not satisfy $Q=C V$. Nevertheless, as the following example demonstrates, a voltage-dependent capacitor leads to intriguing circuit configurations.

Example: A cellphone includes a 2-GHz oscillator whose frequency is determined by the resonance frequency of an $L C \operatorname{tank}$ (Fig. 2.26). If the tank capacitance is realized using the pn junction from Example 2.15, calculate the frequency change as the reverse voltage varies from 0 to 2 V. Assume the circuit operates at 2 GHz at 0 V reverse voltage, with a junction area of $2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}$.
