We aim to reevaluate the results obtained in equilibrium for the reverse bias scenario. First, let's determine if the external voltage reinforces or opposes the built-in electric field. Since, in equilibrium, $\vec{E}$ is directed from the $n$ side to the $p$ side, $V_{R}$ strengthens the field. However, a higher electric field can only be sustained if more fixed charge is available, necessitating the exposure of additional acceptor and donor ions, thus widening the depletion region.

What effect does this have on the diffusion and drift currents? The external voltage, by intensifying the field, raises the barrier even higher than in equilibrium, effectively preventing current flow. In other words, the junction conducts a negligible current under reverse bias. ${ }^{9}$

At first glance, a reverse-biased pn junction might seem impractical due to the lack of current conduction. However, a crucial observation reveals its utility. As illustrated in Fig. 2.23, increasing $V_{B}$ results in more positive charge on the $n$ side and more negative charge on the $p$ side. Thus, the device functions as a capacitor [Fig. 2.24(a)]. Essentially, the conductive $n$ and $p$ sections can be viewed as the capacitor's two plates. We also assume that the charge in the depletion region is equivalently distributed on each plate.

One might still question the device's significance. After all, any two parallel plates can form a capacitor, so using a pn junction for this purpose may seem unjustified. However, reverse-biased $p n$ junctions possess a unique property that is valuable in circuit design. Referring back to Fig. 2.23, we observe that as $V_{R}$ increases, so does the depletion region width. Consequently, the conceptual diagram in Fig. 2.24(a) can be modified as in Fig. 2.24(b) for higher $V_{R}$ values, demonstrating that the capacitance decreases as the plates move apart. Thus, the junction exhibits a voltage-dependent capacitance.

It can be demonstrated that the capacitance per unit area of the junction is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j}=\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1-\frac{V_{R}}{V_{0}}}} \tag{2.75}
\end{equation*}
$$

${ }^{9}$ As detailed in Section 2.2.3, the current is not exactly zero.
where $C_{j 0}$ represents the capacitance at zero bias $\left(V_{R}=0\right)$ and $V_{0}$ is the built-in potential [Eq. (2.69)]. (This equation assumes $V_{R}$ is negative for reverse bias.) The value of $C_{j 0}$ is determined by

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j 0}=\sqrt{\frac{\epsilon_{s i} q}{2} \frac{N_{A} N_{D}}{N_{A}+N_{D}} \frac{1}{V_{0}}} \tag{2.76}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $\epsilon_{s i}$ is the dielectric constant of silicon, equal to $11.7 \times 8.85 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{cm} .{ }^{10}$ As shown in Fig. 2.25, $C_{j}$ decreases with increasing $V_{R}$.
