We aim to reassess the results obtained in equilibrium for the reverse bias scenario. First, let's determine if the external voltage reinforces or opposes the built-in electric field. Since, in equilibrium, $\vec{E}$ is directed from the $n$ side to the $p$ side, $V_{R}$ strengthens this field. However, a higher electric field can only be sustained if more fixed charge is available, necessitating the exposure of additional acceptor and donor ions and thus widening the depletion region.

What effect does this have on diffusion and drift currents? The external voltage, by intensifying the field, raises the barrier even higher than in equilibrium, effectively preventing current flow. In other words, the junction conducts a negligible current under reverse bias. ${ }^{9}$

At first glance, a reverse-biased pn junction might seem impractical due to the lack of current conduction. However, a crucial observation reveals its utility. Notably, in Fig. 2.23, as $V_{B}$ increases, more positive charge accumulates on the $n$ side and more negative charge on the $p$ side, enabling the device to function as a capacitor [Fig. 2.24(a)]. Essentially, the conductive $n$ and $p$ sections can be regarded as the capacitor's plates. We also assume the charge in the depletion region is equivalently distributed on each plate.

Readers might still find this unremarkable, given that any two parallel plates can form a capacitor, making the use of a pn junction for this purpose seemingly unnecessary. However, reverse-biased $p n$ junctions possess a unique property that proves valuable in circuit design. Referring back to Fig. 2.23, we observe that as $V_{R}$ increases, so does the depletion region's width. Thus, the conceptual diagram in Fig. 2.24(a) can be modified as in Fig. 2.24(b) for rising $V_{R}$ values, demonstrating that the structure's capacitance decreases as the plates move apart. Consequently, the junction exhibits a voltage-dependent capacitance.

It can be demonstrated that the junction's capacitance per unit area is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j}=\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1-\frac{V_{R}}{V_{0}}}} \tag{2.75}
\end{equation*}
$$

${ }^{9}$ As detailed in Section 2.2.3, the current is not entirely zero.
where $C_{j 0}$ represents the capacitance at zero bias $\left(V_{R}=0\right)$ and $V_{0}$ is the built-in potential [Eq. (2.69)]. (This equation assumes $V_{R}$ is negative for reverse bias.) The value of $C_{j 0}$ is calculated by

$$
\begin{equation*}
C_{j 0}=\sqrt{\frac{\epsilon_{s i} q}{2} \frac{N_{A} N_{D}}{N_{A}+N_{D}} \frac{1}{V_{0}}} \tag{2.76}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $\epsilon_{s i}$ is the dielectric constant of silicon, equal to $11.7 \times 8.85 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~F} / \mathrm{cm} .{ }^{10}$ As plotted in Fig. 2.25, $C_{j}$ clearly decreases with increasing $V_{R}$.
