description:
[
name: C, type: Capacitor, value: C, ports: {Np: X2, Nn: X1}
name: L, type: Inductor, value: L, ports: {N1: X2, N2: X1}
name: VR, type: VoltageSource, value: VR, ports: {Np: VR, Nn: X1}
]
extrainfo:The circuit is an LC oscillator with a variable capacitor C, an inductor L, and a voltage source VR. Capacitor C is connected between nodes X2 and X1, and inductor L is parallel to the capacitor. The voltage source VR is connected to node X1.

Figure 2.26 Variable capacitor used to tune an oscillator.

Solution Recall from basic circuit theory that the tank resonates when the impedances of the inductor and capacitor are equal and opposite: $j L \omega_{\text {res }}=-\left(j C \omega_{\text {res }}\right)^{-1}$. Thus, the resonance frequency is

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_{\text {res }}=\frac{1}{2 \pi} \frac{1}{\sqrt{L C}} \tag{2.84}
\end{equation*}
$$

At $V_{R}=0, C_{j}=0.265 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2}$, giving a total device capacitance of

$$
\begin{align*}
C_{j, t o t}\left(V_{R}=0\right) & =\left(0.265 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2}\right) \times\left(2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}\right)  \tag{2.85}\\
& =530 \mathrm{fF} . \tag{2.86}
\end{align*}
$$

Setting $f_{\text {res }}$ to 2 GHz, we get

$$
\begin{equation*}
L=11.9 \mathrm{nH} \tag{2.87}
\end{equation*}
$$

If $V_{R}$ increases to 2 V,

$$
\begin{align*}
C_{j, t o t}\left(V_{R}=2 \mathrm{~V}\right) & =\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1+\frac{2}{0.73}}} \times 2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}  \tag{2.88}\\
& =274 \mathrm{fF} . \tag{2.89}
\end{align*}
$$

Using this value and $L=11.9 \mathrm{nH}$ in Eq. (2.84), we find

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_{r e s}\left(V_{R}=2 \mathrm{~V}\right)=2.79 \mathrm{GHz} \tag{2.90}
\end{equation*}
$$

An oscillator whose frequency can be adjusted by an external voltage ( $V_{R}$ in this case) is known as a "voltage-controlled oscillator" and is extensively used in cellphones, microprocessors, personal computers, etc.

Exercise Some wireless systems operate at 5.2 GHz. Repeat the above example for this frequency, assuming the junction area remains $2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}$ but the inductor value is adjusted to achieve 5.2 GHz.

In summary, a reverse-biased $p n$ junction conducts a negligible current but exhibits a voltage-dependent capacitance. Note that we have implicitly developed a circuit model for the device under this condition: a simple capacitance whose value is given by Eq. (2.75).

Another intriguing application of reverse-biased diodes is in digital cameras (Chapter 1). When light of sufficient energy strikes a pn junction, it dislodges electrons from their covalent bonds, creating electron-hole pairs. With a reverse bias, electrons are drawn to the positive battery terminal and holes to the negative terminal, resulting in a current through the diode proportional to the light intensity. Thus, the pn junction functions as a "photodiode."

