C_{j} & =\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1+\frac{V_{R}}{V_{0}}}}  \tag{2.82}\\
& =0.172 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2} \tag{2.83}
\end{align*}
$$

\$\$

Exercise: Repeat the above example if the donor concentration on the $N$ side is doubled. Compare the results in the two cases.

The capacitance variation with applied voltage renders the device a "nonlinear" capacitor, as it does not satisfy $Q=C V$. Nevertheless, as the following example demonstrates, a voltage-dependent capacitor leads to intriguing circuit topologies.

Example: A cellphone includes a 2-GHz oscillator whose frequency is determined by the resonance frequency of an $L C \operatorname{tank}$ (Fig. 2.26). If the tank capacitance is implemented as the $p n$ junction from Example 2.15, calculate the frequency change as the reverse voltage varies from 0 to 2 V. Assume the circuit operates at 2 GHz at a reverse voltage of 0 V, and the junction area is $2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}$.

