Figure 2.26 Variable capacitor used to tune an oscillator.

Solution: Recall from basic circuit theory that the tank "resonates" when the impedances of the inductor and capacitor are equal and opposite: $j L \omega_{\text {res }}=-\left(j C \omega_{\text {res }}\right)^{-1}$. Thus, the resonance frequency is

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_{\text {res }}=\frac{1}{2 \pi} \frac{1}{\sqrt{L C}} \tag{2.84}
\end{equation*}
$$

At $V_{R}=0, C_{j}=0.265 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2}$, giving a total device capacitance of

$$
\begin{align*}
C_{j, t o t}\left(V_{R}=0\right) & =\left(0.265 \mathrm{fF} / \mu \mathrm{m}^{2}\right) \times\left(2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}\right)  \tag{2.85}\\
& =530 \mathrm{fF} . \tag{2.86}
\end{align*}
$$

Setting $f_{\text {res }}$ to 2 GHz, we find

$$
\begin{equation*}
L=11.9 \mathrm{nH} \tag{2.87}
\end{equation*}
$$

If $V_{R}$ increases to 2 V,

$$
\begin{align*}
C_{j, t o t}\left(V_{R}=2 \mathrm{~V}\right) & =\frac{C_{j 0}}{\sqrt{1+\frac{2}{0.73}}} \times 2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}  \tag{2.88}\\
& =274 \mathrm{fF} . \tag{2.89}
\end{align*}
$$

Using this value and $L=11.9 \mathrm{nH}$ in Eq. (2.84), we get

$$
\begin{equation*}
f_{r e s}\left(V_{R}=2 \mathrm{~V}\right)=2.79 \mathrm{GHz} \tag{2.90}
\end{equation*}
$$

An oscillator whose frequency can be adjusted by an external voltage ( $V_{R}$ in this case) is termed a "voltage-controlled oscillator" and is extensively used in cellphones, microprocessors, personal computers, etc.

Exercise: For wireless systems operating at 5.2 GHz, repeat the above example, assuming the junction area remains $2000 \mu \mathrm{~m}^{2}$ but the inductor value is adjusted to achieve 5.2 GHz.

In summary, a reverse-biased $p n$ junction conducts a negligible current but displays a voltage-dependent capacitance. Note that we have implicitly developed a circuit model for the device under this condition: a simple capacitance whose value is given by Eq. (2.75).

Another intriguing application of reverse-biased diodes is in digital cameras (Chapter 1). When light of sufficient energy strikes a pn junction, it dislodges electrons from their covalent bonds, creating electron-hole pairs. With a reverse bias, electrons are drawn to the positive battery terminal and holes to the negative terminal, resulting in a current through the diode proportional to the light intensity. Thus, the pn junction functions as a "photodiode."
